# Section 7 — Model Context Protocol (MCP)

---

# 7.1 Introduction

The **Model Context Protocol (MCP)** is an open communication protocol that enables Large Language Models (LLMs) to interact with external tools, services, and data sources using a standardized interface.

Before MCP, every AI application had to implement custom integrations for each external service.

For example:

```
LLM

↓

Custom Python Code

↓

Google Maps API
```

Another service required another integration.

```
LLM

↓

Custom Code

↓

Tavily API
```

Another service required another implementation.

```
LLM

↓

Custom Code

↓

Database
```

As more tools were added, the application became increasingly difficult to maintain.

MCP solves this problem by introducing a **common communication protocol** between AI models and external capabilities.

Instead of teaching every model how to call every API, MCP standardizes the interaction.

---

# 7.2 Why was MCP created?

Imagine building an AI assistant that needs access to:

- Google Maps
- Slack
- GitHub
- Salesforce
- SAP
- Jira
- Outlook
- Databases
- File Systems

Without MCP, every application developer must write custom integrations for every system.

```
LLM

↓

Custom Integration

↓

Google Maps
```

```
LLM

↓

Different Integration

↓

Slack
```

```
LLM

↓

Different Integration

↓

GitHub
```

Each integration:

- Uses different authentication.
- Uses different request formats.
- Uses different response formats.
- Uses different error handling.

Maintenance quickly becomes expensive.

---

# 7.3 MCP Standardizes Everything

Instead of

```
LLM

↓

API
```

the architecture becomes

```
LLM

↓

MCP

↓

Any Tool
```

The AI model only needs to understand **MCP**.

Every external capability implements the MCP protocol.

This dramatically simplifies tool integration.

---

# 7.4 MCP in This Project

The Study Abroad Finder uses four MCP servers.

```
                 Gemini

                    │

                    ▼

             Google ADK

                    │

      ┌─────────────┼─────────────┐

      ▼             ▼             ▼

 Tavily MCP    Scholarship MCP   Google Maps MCP

                    │

                    ▼

            Filesystem MCP
```

Gemini never communicates directly with:

- Google Maps
- Tavily
- Scholarship APIs
- Filesystem

Instead,

Gemini communicates only with Google ADK.

Google ADK communicates with MCP.

MCP communicates with the actual service.

---

# 7.5 MCP Architecture

A generic MCP architecture looks like this.

```
User

↓

LLM

↓

ADK

↓

MCP Client

↓

MCP Server

↓

External System
```

The MCP server becomes the translator between the AI model and the external service.

---

# 7.6 MCP Client vs MCP Server

The protocol consists of two major components.

## MCP Client

The client lives inside the AI application.

Responsibilities:

- Discover tools
- Open sessions
- Invoke tools
- Send parameters
- Receive responses

In this project,

Google ADK acts as the MCP Client.

---

## MCP Server

The server exposes tools.

Responsibilities:

- Register tools
- Accept requests
- Execute business logic
- Return structured results

Examples

```
Scholarship MCP

↓

get_scholarships()
```

```
Google Maps MCP

↓

get_weather()
```

```
Filesystem MCP

↓

write_file()
```

---

# 7.7 Local MCP vs Remote MCP

MCP servers can run in different environments.

---

## Local MCP

Runs on the same machine as the application.

Communication occurs through

```
STDIO
```

Example

```
Scholarship MCP
```

```
Filesystem MCP
```

Architecture

```
ADK

↓

STDIO

↓

Python Process

↓

Scholarship Server
```

---

## Remote MCP

Runs on another machine.

Communication occurs through

```
HTTP

or

Streamable HTTP
```

Examples

```
Google Maps MCP

↓

Remote
```

```
Tavily MCP

↓

Remote
```

Architecture

```
ADK

↓

HTTP

↓

Remote MCP

↓

External Service
```

---

# 7.8 Why Two Communication Methods?

Different tools have different deployment models.

Local tools

Advantages

- Faster
- Private
- No internet required
- Easier debugging

Remote tools

Advantages

- Centralized
- Always updated
- Shared across applications
- Easier scaling

The Study Abroad Finder intentionally demonstrates both models.

---

# 7.9 MCP Session Lifecycle

Every tool invocation follows a lifecycle.

```
Gemini

↓

Select Tool

↓

ADK

↓

Create MCP Session

↓

Invoke Tool

↓

Receive Result

↓

Close Session
```

Each tool call is isolated.

