# 7.15 Why Filesystem MCP Behaved Differently

One of the biggest discoveries during this project was that not all MCP servers have identical runtime requirements.

The Filesystem MCP is distributed as a Node.js package:

```bash
npx @modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem
```

Unlike the Scholarship MCP (a Python process), the Filesystem MCP depends on:

- Node.js
- npm
- npx

This distinction became important during deployment.

In the local development environment, these dependencies were available.

However, the initial Render deployment used a Python runtime that did not fully support launching the Node-based MCP server.

As a result:

```
ADK

↓

Create Filesystem MCP Session

↓

npx unavailable / runtime mismatch

↓

Session creation fails

↓

Tool unavailable

↓

Request stalls

↓

Worker timeout
```

This was the primary reason Docker became necessary.

---

# 7.16 MCP and Docker

Docker solved the problem by providing a single runtime that included:

- Python
- Node.js
- npm
- npx

Now every MCP server had the runtime it expected.

```
Docker Container

│

├── Python Runtime

├── Node Runtime

├── Scholarship MCP

├── Filesystem MCP

├── Flask

└── Google ADK
```

This ensured consistent behavior between local development and cloud deployment.

---

# 7.17 Lessons Learned

The project produced several important insights about MCP.

### MCP is not an API.

It is a communication protocol.

---

### MCP servers are independent applications.

They can be written in different languages.

---

### One AI agent can communicate with many MCP servers simultaneously.

---

### Local and Remote MCP servers can coexist.

---

### Runtime dependencies matter.

A Python MCP and a Node.js MCP may require different execution environments.

---

### Docker is an excellent way to standardize those environments.

---

# 7.18 Key Takeaways

The Model Context Protocol is the foundation that enables AI agents to move beyond static language generation and interact with external systems in a structured, reusable, and scalable way.

In the Study Abroad Finder project, MCP allowed Gemini to collaborate with multiple specialized services—web search, geographic information, scholarship data, and report generation—without needing to understand the implementation details of those services.

This separation between reasoning (Gemini), orchestration (Google ADK), and execution (MCP servers) is the core architectural principle demonstrated throughout the project and forms the basis for building modular, enterprise-grade AI systems.